            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "The binding directive makes Cython functions/methods use a custom type, instead of Python’s normal C-function type. So `type(my_cython_func) is not type(len)` (though `inspect` works correctly), but the custom type allows them to behave more like pure-Python functions instead of inheriting the builtins’ behaviour. \r\n\r\nThe most obvious change (why it’s called “binding”) is that builtins functions can’t be bound - if you do `myClass.len = len`, calling that on an instance won’t pass self as the first argument. It also allows emulating function attributes, so for example `__defaults__` is set to the right thing - though you can’t write to it.",
            "created_at": "2019-04-14T22:17:26Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/2564#issuecomment-483063048",
